Is price discrimination wrong?

Is price discrimination wrong?

Say I am the lead economist at GoPro. Is it wrong if I:

  • barter with each customer to agree on a price?
  • give a discount if someone buys 10 at once?
  • charge a different price to people who live in different cities?
  • charge a higher price to people who are wearing fancier clothes?

None of these is illegal.

Firms who have some market power dont have to be price-takers

  • Price Discrimination: A selling strategy in which different prices are set for different buyers or groups of buyers, or prices vary depending on the number of units purchased.

Reading: How firms can influence prices.

Price discrimination has three types

  1. first degree: each customer is charged their willingness-to-pay.
  2. second degree: different prices are charged for different quantities purchased (e.g.Costco).
  3. third degree: the market is divided into multiple sub-markets and each is charged a different price

First degree price discrimination

  • Charge each consumer their willingness-to-pay
  • Producers capture all of the surplus

Haggling: The original first degree price discrimination

Second degree price discrimination

  • Different prices for different sizes

E.g. A 16oz. bag of Santitas is $0.18 per oz., an 8oz. bag is $0.154 per oz.

Second degree price discrimination welfare effects

What are the welfare implications for people who have low incomes?

  • they pay more for food because they cant afford bulk purchases.

Third degree price discrimination

  • Divide the market into multiple segments, charge each segment a different price.

Data science: categorizing people

One of the primary jobs for economists at companies like Amazon (or any online retailer) is to use peoples data to categorize them into bins so you can charge a different price.

Evidence for categorization

Categorization gone bad

Categorization happens not just for market transactions. The excellent book Weapons of Math Destruction discusses algorithms that categorize people and determine:

  • prison sentence based on likelihood of recidivism
  • ads for predatory loans displayed on google to people with low incomes
  • hiring practices that replicate bias in past hiring decisions

So when is categorization wrong?
